## Step 3 — Find Currently Running High CPU Queries

Catch the queries burning CPU **right now**:

```sql
SELECT TOP 20
    r.session_id,
    r.status,
    r.cpu_time,
    r.total_elapsed_time / 1000        AS elapsed_secs,
    r.logical_reads,
    r.reads                             AS physical_reads,
    r.writes,
    r.wait_type,
    r.wait_time / 1000.0               AS wait_secs,
    DB_NAME(r.database_id)             AS database_name,
    t.text                             AS query_text,
    qp.query_plan
FROM sys.dm_exec_requests r
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_sql_text(r.sql_handle) t
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_query_plan(r.plan_handle) qp
WHERE r.session_id > 50
  AND r.status = 'running'
ORDER BY r.cpu_time DESC;
```

> **Tip:** Click `query_plan` in SSMS results to open graphical execution plan. Look for **Table Scan**, **Hash Match**, and **Sort** operators with large row counts — these are the CPU hogs.

