## Step 5 — Check for Excessive Parallelism (CXPACKET)

Uncontrolled parallelism is one of the top CPU killers. One query can consume ALL CPU cores simultaneously:

```sql
-- Check CXPACKET wait stats
SELECT 
    wait_type,
    waiting_tasks_count,
    wait_time_ms / 1000.0              AS total_wait_secs,
    wait_time_ms * 100.0 /
    SUM(wait_time_ms) OVER()           AS pct_of_total_waits
FROM sys.dm_os_wait_stats
WHERE wait_type IN ('CXPACKET', 'CXCONSUMER', 'SOS_SCHEDULER_YIELD')
ORDER BY wait_time_ms DESC;
```

```sql
-- Check current MAXDOP and Cost Threshold settings
SELECT name, value_in_use, description
FROM sys.configurations
WHERE name IN (
    'max degree of parallelism',
    'cost threshold for parallelism'
);
```

**Recommended settings:**

| Setting | Default | Recommended |
|---|---|---|
| Max Degree of Parallelism (MAXDOP) | 0 (unlimited) | Number of physical cores per NUMA node, max 8 |
| Cost Threshold for Parallelism | 5 | 25 – 50 |

```sql
-- Fix: Set MAXDOP and Cost Threshold
EXEC sp_configure 'max degree of parallelism', 4;       -- adjust to your core count
EXEC sp_configure 'cost threshold for parallelism', 50;
RECONFIGURE WITH OVERRIDE;
```

> **Note:** On Azure SQL VM, check how many vCPUs your VM has first.
> `Azure Portal → VM → Overview → vCPUs`

