## Step 9 — Detect and Fix Parameter Sniffing

Parameter sniffing occurs when SQL Server caches an execution plan built for one set of parameter values, but the plan is terrible for different values. This can cause runaway CPU usage:

```sql
-- Check if a query has multiple plans with wildly different resource usage
SELECT 
    qs.execution_count,
    qs.total_worker_time / qs.execution_count / 1000  AS avg_cpu_ms,
    qs.min_worker_time / 1000                          AS min_cpu_ms,
    qs.max_worker_time / 1000                          AS max_cpu_ms,
    qs.total_logical_reads / qs.execution_count        AS avg_logical_reads,
    t.text                                             AS query_text,
    qp.query_plan
FROM sys.dm_exec_query_stats qs
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_sql_text(qs.sql_handle) t
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_query_plan(qs.plan_handle) qp
WHERE (qs.max_worker_time / NULLIF(qs.min_worker_time, 0)) > 10  -- max CPU 10x higher than min
ORDER BY qs.max_worker_time DESC;
```

**If `max_cpu_ms` is 10x higher than `avg_cpu_ms` → parameter sniffing is likely.**

```sql
-- Fix Option 1: Clear the plan cache for a specific query
-- Get plan handle from query above, then:
DBCC FREEPROCCACHE (plan_handle);

-- Fix Option 2: Add OPTION (RECOMPILE) to force fresh plan each time
SELECT * FROM Orders WHERE CustomerId = @CustomerId
OPTION (RECOMPILE);

-- Fix Option 3: Use OPTIMIZE FOR hint
SELECT * FROM Orders WHERE CustomerId = @CustomerId
OPTION (OPTIMIZE FOR (@CustomerId UNKNOWN));
```

