## Step 10 — Check for Implicit Conversions

Implicit conversions happen when SQL Server compares columns of different data types. It silently converts every row in the table, bypassing indexes and burning CPU:

```sql
-- Find implicit conversions in execution plans
SELECT 
    DB_NAME(qp.dbid)          AS database_name,
    OBJECT_NAME(qp.objectid)  AS object_name,
    t.text                    AS query_text,
    qp.query_plan
FROM sys.dm_exec_cached_plans cp
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_query_plan(cp.plan_handle) qp
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_sql_text(cp.plan_handle) t
WHERE CAST(qp.query_plan AS NVARCHAR(MAX)) LIKE '%CONVERT_IMPLICIT%';
```

**Common causes and fixes:**

| Cause | Example | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| varchar vs nvarchar | `WHERE Name = N'value'` on varchar column | Match data types in query and table |
| int vs varchar | `WHERE Id = '123'` where Id is INT | Remove quotes: `WHERE Id = 123` |
| Date as string | `WHERE OrderDate = '2024-01-01'` | Use `CAST('2024-01-01' AS DATE)` |

