## Step 11 — Check Stored Procedures and Ad-Hoc SQL Recompiles

Excessive recompiles force SQL Server to regenerate execution plans repeatedly, burning CPU:

```sql
-- Find objects with high recompile rates
SELECT TOP 20
    OBJECT_NAME(ps.object_id)              AS object_name,
    ps.type_desc,
    ps.execution_count,
    ps.total_recompile_count,
    ps.total_recompile_count * 100.0 / 
    NULLIF(ps.execution_count, 0)          AS recompile_pct,
    ps.total_worker_time / 1000            AS total_cpu_ms
FROM sys.dm_exec_procedure_stats ps
WHERE ps.total_recompile_count > 0
ORDER BY ps.total_recompile_count DESC;
```

**Common recompile causes and fixes:**

| Cause | Fix |
|---|---|
| DDL changes inside stored proc | Move DDL outside or use `WITH RECOMPILE` intentionally |
| SET options changing per connection | Standardize SET options in application connection string |
| Temp table stats changing | Add `OPTION (RECOMPILE)` to queries using temp tables |
| Statistics updated mid-execution | Expected — only a concern if frequency is very high |

