## Step 13 — Infrastructure Fix (Azure SQL VM)

If the queries are tuned but CPU is still maxed, the VM needs more compute power.

### 13.1 — Check Current VM Size

```
Azure Portal → Virtual Machine → Overview → Size
```

### 13.2 — Resize VM for More CPU

```
Azure Portal → Virtual Machine → Size → Select larger size → Resize
```

**Recommended SQL Server VM sizes (General Purpose):**

| Workload | VM Series | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Dev / Test | Standard_D4s_v5 (4 vCPU) | Cost effective |
| Small Prod | Standard_D8s_v5 (8 vCPU) | Good balance |
| Medium Prod | Standard_E16s_v5 (16 vCPU) | Memory optimized |
| Heavy OLTP | Standard_M32s (32 vCPU) | High memory ratio |

> **Rule of thumb:** Choose memory-optimized (E-series) over compute-optimized for SQL Server. More RAM means less disk I/O which reduces CPU work.

### 13.3 — Enable Accelerated Networking

Reduces CPU overhead for network packet processing:

```
Azure Portal → VM → Networking → Network Interface → Enable Accelerated Networking
```

