## Common Causes Summary

| Cause | Fix | Step |
|---|---|---|
| MAXDOP = 0 (unlimited parallelism) | Set MAXDOP to core count, max 8 | Step 5 |
| Cost Threshold for Parallelism too low | Increase from 5 to 50 | Step 5 |
| Missing indexes → table scans | Create missing indexes | Step 6 |
| Fragmented indexes | Rebuild / Reorganize indexes | Step 7 |
| Outdated statistics | Run UPDATE STATISTICS | Step 8 |
| Parameter sniffing | OPTION (RECOMPILE) or OPTIMIZE FOR | Step 9 |
| Implicit data type conversions | Fix data types in queries | Step 10 |
| Excessive stored proc recompiles | Fix DDL and SET options | Step 11 |
| VM CPU cores maxed out | Resize to larger Azure VM size | Step 13.2 |
| Antivirus scanning SQL folders | Exclude SQL data directories | Step 13 |

---

## Related Wait Types

| Wait Type | Relationship |
|---|---|
| `CXPACKET` | Parallelism wait — directly tied to high CPU from parallel queries |
| `CXCONSUMER` | Consumer thread in parallel plan waiting — pair with CXPACKET |
| `SOS_SCHEDULER_YIELD` | CPU fully saturated — threads yielding scheduler time |
| `SOS_WORKER_MIGRATION` | Worker threads migrating between schedulers under CPU pressure |
| `RESOURCE_SEMAPHORE` | Memory grants queued — often caused by same queries burning CPU |
| `PAGEIOLATCH_SH` | If CPU is high AND this is high — missing indexes causing scans |

